    "question_text": "Will US federal agencies cease international arrival processing at any of the following airports for 3 or more consecutive days before 2027?",
    "probability": 0.19,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately **206 days** from June 8, 2026 to January 1, 2027.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf the Trump administration abandons or significantly delays these plans, no processing cessation occurs and the question resolves NO. This is the most likely path given:\n- No formal policy has been issued as of June 8, 2026\n- DHS Secretary Mullin explicitly stated the effort is \"not initiating yet\"\n- Immediate implementation during the FIFA World Cup window (June 2026) would create massive diplomatic and logistical problems\n- Legal challenges would likely delay or prevent implementation\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Legal injunctions block implementation before any 3-day cessation occurs\n- Political/diplomatic pressure (allied nations, business groups, Congress) forces abandonment\n- Administrative delays push any implementation past January 1, 2027\n- Implementation occurs in very limited form at non-major airports, avoiding the listed hubs\n- Court challenges succeed on constitutional or statutory grounds before operational cessation\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Administration rapidly drafts formal policy (late June-July 2026)\n- Implementation begins at a single targeted airport (likely SFO, LAX, or JFK given sanctuary city focus)\n- Despite legal challenges, the administration maintains the processing halt for \u22653 consecutive days\n- Court orders to restore service either come after the 3-day window or are ignored initially\n- Political will overrides normal institutional resistance to such disruption\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nHistorical precedent for federal agencies unilaterally ceasing major airport services:\n- **Airline strikes/slowdowns**: Common (1-2 major ones per decade), but these are labor actions, not government-initiated\n- **Government-ordered service suspensions**: Extremely rare in US airport operations history\n- **CBP operations halts**: Never before has CBP ceased international arrival processing at a major hub for political reasons\n- **FAA ATC strikes/slowdowns**: 1981 (controller strike), but not a government shutdown of the system itself\n- **General airport closures**: Only for weather, security threats, or emergency maintenance\u2014not political/jurisdictional disputes\n\nThe **base rate for a US federal agency deliberately ceasing major airport services for political reasons is approximately 2-5% per year** for a given airport in the modern era, heavily skewed toward the rare extreme outlier category.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors increasing probability from base rate:**\n- **Current administration stated intent**: DHS Secretary publicly announced plans on major news network (May 27, 2026)\n- **Specificity of targets**: Multiple major airports named explicitly, suggesting some planning has occurred\n- **Political mandate**: Trump administration has shown willingness to pursue contentious policies despite legal/institutional opposition\n- **Time window**: ~7 months is sufficient to draft policy, navigate initial legal challenges, and attempt implementation\n- **Historical precedent in this administration**: Trump's first term showed willingness to challenge sanctuary city policies through various federal levers\n\n**Factors decreasing probability from base rate:**\n- **No formal policy yet**: As of June 8, 2026, this remains in the \"drawing up plans\" phase\u2014significant gap between rhetoric and implementation\n- **Massive operational/economic disruption**: Airlines, airport operators, and business community would mobilize aggressively against this\n- **Legal landscape is hostile**: Federal courts have consistently blocked immigration-related actions targeting sanctuary jurisdictions; this would face immediate injunctions\n- **FIFA World Cup timing**: Implementation during June 2026 is politically untenable; pushing to July+ reduces time for resolution period\n- **Congressional opposition**: Even Republican-controlled Congress would likely oppose disruption at major economic hubs\n- **Institutional inertia**: CBP, TSA, and airport operators have massive resistance to such disruptions\n- **International diplomatic costs**: Would damage US travel/commerce relationships\n- **Only 206 days remaining**: Very tight timeline for formal policy + implementation + survival through 3-day window before legal relief\n\n## (g) Community prediction and divergence\n\nI don't have access to a specific community forecast on this question, but typical forecaster consensus on politically contentious Trump administration policies ranges from 25-45% depending on institutional resistance levels. \n\nIf community forecast exists and is significantly different, I would diverge if:\n- Community is >60%: I believe they're underweighting institutional/legal resistance and the tight timeline\n- Community is <15%: I believe they're underweighting this administration's demonstrated willingness to pursue such policies\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nThis question requires **both** stated intent AND operational implementation AND survival through legal challenges within a 206-day window.\n\n**Probability decomposition:**\n- P(formal policy drafted and issued) = ~60% (credible stated intent, but administrative delays and legal pre-emptive challenges likely)\n- P(implementation attempted at \u22651 major airport | policy issued) = ~55% (political will present, but legal injunctions highly likely before implementation)\n- P(cessation lasts \u22653 consecutive days | implementation attempted) = ~40% (courts would likely issue emergency stays within 24-48 hours; administration might resist but Supreme Court intervention highly likely)\n\nCombined: 0.60 \u00d7 0.55 \u00d7 0.40 = **13.2%**\n\nHowever, adjusting upward slightly (to ~18-20%) for:\n- Possibility that administration moves faster than expected (summer 2026 implementation push)\n- Small chance of successful legal delay (case stays through Jan 1, 2027)\n- Possibility of limited implementation at non-major airports that still meets criteria\n\nAdjusting downward slightly for:\n- Extreme timeline pressure in final months of 2026\n- Diplomatic/economic backlash forcing abandonment\n\n**Probability: 19%**",
